 existing programs, the faster the flywheel spins, the deeper the moats go,=
 and the harder it is for anyone to compete with On Deck.=C2=A0
As we=E2=80=99ll dig into below, On Deck=E2=80=99s accumulated institutiona=
l program-building expertise allows it to get creative with who it taps to =
lead programs. Instead of hiring for educational experience, it can hire fo=
r passion, expertise, and audience, all of which increase On Deck=E2=80=99s=
 awareness and credibility.=C2=A0
Looking at the programs together, On Deck is building what co-founder Erik =
Torenberg calls [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEuKwzAMQE8TL4P8TbLwY=
mDoNYI_Smqa2MFRZujtx20XA0aWENITLzjCtdSnPcpJ7BVmeh5oM_6eGxJhZdeJdU7RciNGqdXE=
olWRj3pk6ZyXiri7tFmqF7Lj8lsKjlLJ7wkAodndyhhkBPQRvA96GZQxk-dqMUbBoMb44borJsw=
BLf5gfZaMbLN3ouPs5Fcnbu3Rb3pd1IeytwprelCpmD3WtdUnObrOlnCp-dQgEmDUyozcQCdvbc=
23AJasAMFBCs0HKeTU8z4EaeLgx7DIECMOWqGEcXEDwGJQiE7Bvor-vHxDhMcLz6rNhXypKa-t_=
bi7Hbd3oymY279fOdFzxuz8hvFjhz6S377mFTPWJj_Ojppa3pRIbSaY5MdG0yeVmECLiTVyLG0q=
_0P_AG1JkNI], =E2=80=9CStanford for the Internet.=E2=80=9D Today, On Deck i=
s where top talent, from anywhere in the world, goes to kickstart an increa=
sing number of paths in tech and the creator economy; over time, it should =
be able to plug anything that people want to learn or build together into i=
ts infrastructure.=C2=A0
Specifically, it has two products:
A new approach to continuous online education: delivered through synchronou=
s 'cohorts' of 100 - 200 individuals, with an emphasis on peer-to-peer lear=
ning. In 2021, On Deck will launch up to 120 of these cohorts across ~30 ca=
tegories, driving substantial upfront cash flow.
A private, professional social network. Serving as the "campus" to On Deck=
=E2=80=99s "college," the On Deck product is a =E2=80=9Cmarket network [htt=
ps://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEtuxCAMhk8zLCPegQWLbnqNiICTQZNABE6r3L7MZ=
FHJ8kOW_dtf8AhrqZc7SkPydhNeB7gMv20DRKjkbFCnFB3T3AglLYlORmaUIalNSwXYfdoc1hPI=
cc5bCh5TyZ8JSrkiT2e5oLNZQlw4jNqKYHSEuCivlKFS0FvXnzFBDuDgB-pVMpDNPRGP9hBfD_7=
dDX_T-6IhlL1XM5QcIbx62tDj2XrChFSWSS05ZUpRLQUnyXHKGRVcsVFwYQc2hCB0HGcTFhFihF=
FJENQsfqR00cD5Q9J95UM75745vN6CpLpccC415bW3X0-_w_Zp9KenHvczJ7wmyH7eIN488Mb6I=
TStkKF23HHy2GEy3UkobakV9_8dmJDcUsUt6cqx9Kn8L_oHgIeMWw]=E2=80=9D facilitatin=
g matching between talent and opportunity, knowledge, and more. It=E2=80=99=
s LinkedIn and AngelList meet Quora, and it=E2=80=99s one way that On Deck =
will be able to continue to charge subscription revenue long after each Fel=
lowship ends.
Now if you=E2=80=99re like the investors I spoke to when I was thinking abo=
ut Not Boring Club, despite everything I wrote above, you might hear the wo=
rds =E2=80=9Ccommunity=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ceducation=E2=80=9D and head fo=
r the exits.=C2=A0
WAIT! You might want to hear On Deck=E2=80=99s numbers first.=C2=A0
On Deck is an education business with software margins: On Deck turned a pr=
ofit in 2020, and entered 2021 on a ~$20M run rate. On Deck is known for it=
s consumer-facing programs, but it currently has five revenue streams:=C2=
=A0
Consumer-Facing Programs. The bread and butter, these cover everything from=
 the Founders Fellowship I was a part of to On Deck Writers.=C2=A0
Career Programs. Like the YPO for X, these are ongoing professional organiz=
ations that people should be able to expense out of their L&D budgets, for =
example On Deck Scale, and the new Design and Chief of Staff programs.=C2=
=A0
Partnerships. On Deck has annual partnerships with 17 partners like Stripe,=
 Carta, Mercury, and Substack.
Recruiting. On Deck recently acquired Lean Hire [https://email.mg2.substack=
=2Ecom/c/eJxFkMuOhSAQRL_msjQ8BGXBYjb3Nwi=
PVslVMNjOxL8fRheTdLoXlerKqeAQ5lIvs5cD=
yd-yeO1gMvwcKyBCJecB1aZomOKjkL0m0fSRjXIk6bBTBdhcWg3WE8h--jUFh6nk20Epl2Qxzjv=
G2CSU9IFqzaMEEJEPE8QhUDc-ue6MCXIAA99Qr5KBrGZB3F_i68XfbVZweUkVulA2kgynnFHBJR=
sEF7pjXQhCxcGPYRIhRhhkD4KOkxsonRRw_urpNvPuOP2BLnzuN9Xkgr7UlOcmfxa3wXoLDcW2u=
5054WUhO79CfCjxKevmtjNkqK3EaB22iphSWkilqRYPVatB9FxTyTVpybE0V_4P_QVYb4ER], w=
hich should benefit dramatically by being plugged into the On Deck Network.=
=C2=A0
Digital Subscription Bundle. On Deck is launching an ongoing subscription t=
o keep program participants engaged over the course of their careers.
With these programs and products, and new ones launching seemingly weekly, =
On Deck is on track to 10x again in the next 2-3 years. When you zoom out, =
what On Deck is building looks less like an educational institution and mor=
e like a really great internet business.=C2=A0
What makes a great internet business? It=E2=80=99s pretty simple: acquire c=
ustomers cheaply, sell them more things, get operating leverage, produce st=
rong margins, and build moats to protect it all.=C2=A0Look at On Deck:
Low CAC. On Deck doesn=E2=80=99t pay much for marketing. Instead, referrals=
 from existing fellows constitute one of its biggest channels, with over 2,=
500 direct referrals to ODF alone. Plus, with each new high-profile program=
 lead or participant, On Deck=E2=80=99s surface area and attractiveness gro=
ws.=C2=A0
Revenue expansion. Most educational institutions get customers for four yea=
rs, and then spend the rest of their lives asking for donations. On Deck is=
 able to cross-sell multiple programs and products to each Fellow, includin=
g an ongoing subscription.
High upfront costs, low marginal costs. On Deck is building a platform on t=
op of which it can launch new programs and products more cheaply and quickl=
y.=C2=A0
High margins. Despite requiring real live humans, On Deck is already profit=
able because it maintains pricing power compared to competitors [https://em=
ail.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OhCAMgJ9GjoYfRThw2GQzr0EQqpJRMFhn4tsvMx42aShN=
037weYcw53KZPR9IPofFaweT4H2sgAiFnAcUG4NhkivRd5oE0wWmekXiYacCsLm4GiwnkP0c1-g=
dxpy-E5TynixGSCddUF71gfrBjzDBCMFTKrh3IKeb684QIXkw8IJy5QRkNQvifjTip-GPGviOnx=
e1Pm-1Cu4Vg7VjzrjU8kCH51EvTDCumKY904NmilNFG_GoW345JdFwylkF92wQXOiWtd4LGYZR-=
Un4EGDoOxBUTW6gdJLAedPRbebtcY4V4Z8fOikmZRxziWmu7efiNli_jWrA1rydKeJlIblxhXDL=
wdvxV5edIUGp7oN1WM0yKbXopaZa3DKqPdHx-gmuSSWHXKfSP_QP7iKRVQ] (although it=E2=
=80=99s 1% as expensive as an MBA).=C2=A0=C2=A0
Moats.=C2=A0As the network behind On Deck scales, an increasing share of it=
s =E2=80=9Cutility=E2=80=9D comes through the network participants unlock t=
hrough joining =E2=80=94 which becomes increasingly hard to compete with ov=
er time. See Exhibit A: Linkedin.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s taken On Deck years to build its reputation and network. Invit=
e-only dinners turned into Founder Fellowships turned into the growing netw=
ork it is today. Now that it has the lead, it=E2=80=99s built to compound. =
The flywheel that makes On Deck valuable to participants also means that On=
 Deck digs deeper moats with every program it creates, every new cohort tha=
t enters, and every connection it makes among everything that it does.
It=E2=80=99s building a modern educational institution that looks nothing l=
ike the ones it aims to replace.
